evelopment alongside the evolution of the science of toxicology and tracks legislation governing exposure to chemicals across the twentieth century. He affirms the brilliance of Carson’s careful scientific interpretations drawing on data from university and government toxicologists. Although Silent Spring instigated legislation that successfully terminated DDT use, other warnings were ignored. Ironically, we replaced one poison with even more toxic ones. Davis concludes that we urgently need new thinking about how we evaluate and regulate pesticides in accounting for their ecological and human toll.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPesticidesxEnvironmental aspects. 0aPesticidesxHistory. 0aPesticidesxLaw and legislation. 0aPesticidesxToxicology. 0aPesticides. 0aToxicology. 7aSCIENCE / Chemistry / Toxicology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030020517640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021037840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300210378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300210378/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY